1. Introduction

The Friday following Thanksgiving Day is called a Black Friday in the United States. It has been reportedly the busiest shopping day in the United States since 2005. Black Friday is particularly important for retailers since sales on this day affects investor confidence. Investors make predictions for sales on a Black Friday and if the retailers indicate good sales, investors get an indication of a profitable shopping season. Hence, there is an increase in the stock price of such retail companies. Thus, analysis of historical customer data on Black Fridays to realize important customer segments, their preferred products and targeting advertisements to the right customers is essential for retailers to increase sales and gain the confidence of their investors. By forecasting sales on a Black Friday from historic data, retailers can accordingly stock requisite quantities of products in their inventory to minimize missed sales as much as possible.

2. About the Dataset

The Black Friday Sales Dataset was downloaded from Kaggle

(https://www.kaggle.com/sdolezel/black-friday). The dataset provides attributes related to customers and the products they have purchased on a Black Friday. The information about the customers is in an encoded format i.e. the actual information is masked (eg. Cities have been encoded as A, B and C, Age has been discretized as 0-17, 18-25 and so on, thereby hiding the actual age of the customer, etc.) This section briefly describes each column of the dataset before diving into visual analysis :

1.    User_ID: Unique identifier for a user

2.    Product_ID: Unique identifier for a product 3. Gender: Gender of the customer

4.    Age: The age group a customer belongs to

5.    Occupation: The occupation a customer works in (encoded)

6.    City_Category: The city a customer resides in.

7.    Stay_In_Current_City_Years: How many years has the customer resided in their current city.

8.    Marital_Status: Is the customer single or married?

9.    Product_Category_1 : First level categorization of the product 10.Product_Category_2: Second level of product categorization

11.Product_Category_3: Third level of product categorization.

Example : A product may have 3 levels of categorization. Consider the products Beer and Milk Shake. These products may be categorized as:

Beverages → Alcoholic → Beer

Beverages → Dairy → Milk Shake

Here, Beverages is the first level of categorization, Alcoholic and Dairy are the second levels of categorization. Not all products may have second or third levels of categorization. Every product will certainly have a first level of categorization.

12.Purchase: The amount spent by the user on a particular product in USD.

3. Data Preprocessing and Preparation for Regression algorithms

3.1 Split the dataset into training and testing sets

The Black Friday Sales dataset was split into training and test sets. A 80:20 split was used i.e. 80% of the dataset was used for training and remaining 20% for testing. The output of the code snippet below shows that 4,40,054 rows were used in training whereas 1,10,014 were kept for testing.

3.2 Data preprocessing

3.2.1 Check for missing values

The output below shows that the columns Product_Category_2 and

Product_Category_3 have several missing values.

3.2.2 Handle missing values

The column Product_Category_2 has 32% missing values, which were imputed by 0. Here, 0 indicates that the particular product doesnt have a second level categorization. For eg. certain products such as beer may have a 2 level categorization. Beer is a beverage (category 1) and is also alcoholic (category

2).

The column Product_Category_3 has 70% missing values. Hence, it was dropped.

3.2.3 Convert Age to numeric data type.

The Age groups were converted to a numeric value by replacing them with the bin midpoint. For example : the age group 0-17 was replaced (17-0+1)/2 = 9 in the dataset. Similar transformation was applied for other age groups.

3.2.4 One hot encode categorical columns

Categorical variables need to be encoded before fitting machine learning algorithms. The dataset has several categorical features such as Age Group (converted to numeric), Gender, City_Category, Occupation,

Stay_In_Current_City_Years, Product_Category_1, Product_Category_2. These categorical variables had different data types initially. Some were character vectors (Gender, City_Category), while others were integers (Product_Category_1, Occupation). Hence, these were first converted to a consistent data type i.e. a factor in R. Next, the above mentioned columns were one-hot encoded. The number of distinct values in the categorical columns are small (total of 38 as shown in the first screenshot) as compared to the number of rows (5 lakh 50 thousand). Hence, one-hot encoding was chosen for encoding the categorical variables in training and test sets.

3.3 Replace Product_ID with average product price

The column Product_ID doesnt provide any information about the product to a machine learning algorithm. Hence, it needs to be dropped. However, we decided to use the mean expenditure made by customers on each product ID in the training set as a feature, since this information would be significant to a machine learning algorithm. The same feature was added in the test set. Since, there may exist product IDs in the test set which dont exist in the training set, it may introduce some NAs or missing values in the test. To tackle this, we simply impute the missing values by the average of all product prices in the training set.

3.4 Replace User_ID with average buying power

Similar to Product_ID, User_ID doesnt tell much about the customer to a machine learning algorithm. Hence, it needs to be dropped. However, we decided to use the mean expenditure made by customers at the store on a Black Friday in the training set as a feature since it provides useful information to machine learning algorithms. The same feature was added in the test set.

3.5 Drop redundant columns

The columns User_ID, Product_ID are redundant and are replaced by corresponding features such as Average buying power of the Customer and Average expenditure on Product. Also, some redundant columns are introduced by one-hot encoding which can be dropped. For example : one-hot encoding City_Category creates three columns City_Category_A, City_Category_B and City_Category_C. The column City_Category_C is redundant. This is because the encoding [0 0] is sufficient to indicate that a customer neither belongs to city A, encoded as [1 0] and neither does he/she belong to city B, encoded as [0 1]. Similar reasoning can be applied for other redundant columns. Hence, these columns were also dropped to prevent the risk of overfitting due to the curse of dimensionality.

Screenshot of preprocessed dataset :

The preprocessed dataset has 68 columns, few of which are shown in the figure below.

3.6 Standardize numeric features

Standardization is an important preprocessing step before fitting a regression model. This is because if the feature variables are not standardized, the features with larger values will tend to dominate those with small values. For example, the feature avg_price may have values on the scale of thousands whereas a feature like Age may have values in order of tens. A machine learning model may disregard age over average price. Hence, standardization of all numeric features is carried out by subtracting the mean and dividing by the standard deviation of the corresponding column. This ensures all the numeric features have the same scale.

The above output shows the estimated values of coefficients of the linear regression model along with the standard error and a p-value. The p-value indicates whether a feature is statistically significant in predicting the target variable or not. If the p-value > 0.05 (significance level), it can be inferred that the predictor variable is insignificant towards the prediction. Hence, such variables can be dropped.

4.1.2 Making predictions with multiple linear regression model

The adjusted R-squared of the linear regression model is 0.742 which implies that nearly 74.2% of the variance in the target variable (Purchase) can be explained by the predictor variables used in the linear regression model.

As the target variable (Purchase) was standardized during pre-processing, it is required to de-standardize the predicted Purchase amounts so that it is interpretable. De-standardization can be achieved by multiplying by the standard deviation and mean of the purchase amounts in the training dataset (as shown in the figure below).

The first output shows the predicted purchase amounts and the second output represents the actual purchase amounts. We can see that the predicted values closely estimate the actual values!

The performance of the model on the test set was evaluated using metrics such as R squared, Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE). It can be observed that R squared on the testing set is around 0.735 which is close to that on the training set (0.74).

Hence, the model has not overfit the data. The RMSE and MAE are around 2583 USD and

1914 USD respectively.

4.4 Generalized Additive Model (GAM)

GAMs offer a middle ground between simple machine learning models such as linear regression and complex models such as neural networks or gradient boosted regression trees. Linear regression models are often easier to interpret ; however, we often need to model complex phenomena which cannot be captured by linear relationships. Neural networks on the other hand are very good at modelling complex functions however are difficult to interpret (black box) and require a lot of data to optimize the large number of parameters. GAMs are highly flexible at modelling non-linear relationships ; which can also be a downside since these models can easily overfit.

4.4.1 Fitting the GAM model

GAM models are fitted with the help of splines or smooth functions which can take a wide variety of shapes to model non-linear relationships. These splines are a weighted sum of a number of basis functions. The mgcv package in R provides the gam() function for fitting a GAM model. The independent variables average item price and average buying power of the user are wrapped in the s() or smooth function whereas a linear combination of the categorical variables Gender and Marital Status was used, as shown in the code snippet below. The model summary shows the coefficients of the basis function that compose the splines for average price and average buying power.

The above table compares the performance of the regression models on the testing set against evaluation metrics such as Mean Absolute Error, Root Mean Squared Error and R squared. The results show that the XGBoost model achieved the highest R squared of 0.755, which means it can explain nearly 75.5% of the variance in the Purchase amount given the predictor variables such as the Age, Gender, Occupation, Number of years lived in the city, average buying power of the customer and average price of an item.

The models are approximately arranged in the order of their complexity. Multiple linear regression (simplest) uses a linear combination of the predictor variables, whereas polynomial regression adds polynomial terms to the predicted value. GAMs use a weighted sum of non-linear basis functions to approximate the target variable and XGBoost (highest complexity) is an ensemble model of regression trees. The time complexity of GAM and XGBoost were significantly higher than the simpler models such as multiple linear regression, polynomial regression and Decision Tree.

The Decision Tree model had the lowest R squared. This could have been improved by using a collection of Decision Trees rather than a single one i.e. a Random Forest. We attempted to fit a random forest model as well. However, since the training set had around 4 lakh rows and 67 features (after pre-processing), it took an unusually long time to build the model (> 3 hours). Hence, we discarded the random forest model.
